 <title>Cloud Installation</title>
 <chapter xml:id="cloudinstallation_overview">
 <title>Overview</title>
  <para>
   Before starting the installation, review the sample configurations offered
   by &productname; in <xref linkend="example_configurations"/>.
   &productname; ships with highly tuned example configurations for each of
   these cloud models:
  </para>
  <itemizedlist>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <xref linkend="entry-scale-kvm"/>
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <xref linkend="entry-scale-kvm-esx"/>
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <xref linkend="entryscale_swift"/>
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <xref linkend="mid-scale-kvm"/>
    </para>
   </listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
  <xi:include xpointer="element(/1/2)" href="planning+installation-example_config_xpointer.xml"/>
  <para>
   <emphasis role="bold">Using the Command-line</emphasis>
  </para>
  <para>
   You should use the command-line if:
  </para>
  <itemizedlist xml:id="idg-installation-installation-cloudinstallation_overview-xml-7">
   <listitem>
    <para>
     You are installing a more complex or large-scale cloud.
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     You need to use availability zones or the server groups functionality of
     the cloud model. For more information, see the
     <xref linkend="cha.input-model-intro-concept"/>.
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     You want to customize the cloud configuration beyond the tuned defaults
     that &vendor; provides out of the box.
    </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     You need deeper customizations than are possible to express using the GUI.
    </para>
   </listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
  <para>
   Instructions for installing via the command-line are here:
  </para>
  <itemizedlist>
   <listitem>
    <para>
     <xref linkend="install_kvm"/>
    </para>
   </listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
